>https://foodpoisoningbulletin.com/2024/sonora-mexico-rocky-point-oysters-l=
inked-to-norovirus-outbreak/</a>=0D<br>=0D<br>=0D<br>Sonora Mexico Rocky Po=
int Oysters are linked to a norovirus outbreak<br>in San Diego County, acco=
rding to public health officials. At least 41<br>confirmed and probable cas=
es of norovirus have been reported.=0D<br>=0D<br>People started getting sic=
k in mid-December 2023 after eating the raw<br>oysters. The patient age ran=
ge is from 12 to 83 years.=0D<br>=0D<br>These oysters are only available th=
rough restaurants and wholesale<br>distributors. The County Health and Huma=
n Services Agency has asked<br>restaurants not to serve Rocky Point Oysters=
 packed by GOLPAC in Bahia<br>Salina, Sonora, Mexico until further notice.=0D=
<br>=0D<br>The illnesses are tied to oysters served at 3 locations of the F=
ish<br>Shop, in Pacific Beach, Point Loma, and Encinitas, as well as at the=
<br>Carlsbad Aquafarm. The county is investigating to see if the oysters<br=
>were served at other locations.=0D<br>=0D<br>Norovirus is the leading caus=
e of food poisoning in the USA. The virus<br>is very contagious and can be =
spread through contaminated food and<br>drink as well as through person-to-=
person contact and contact with<br>families, or hard surfaces. In fact, som=
e household members of people<br>who ate those oysters have been sick.=0D<b=
r>=0D<br>Symptoms of a norovirus infection usually begin within 12 to 48 ho=
urs<br>of exposure. Patients usually suffer from nausea, vomiting, diarrhea=
,<br>stomach pain, headaches, and body aches. Most people recover on their<=
br>own without medical care, but some may become dehydrated and need to<br>=
be hospitalized. None of the cases in this outbreak needed<br>hospitalizati=
on.=0D<br>=0D<br>Wilma Wooten, MD, MPH, County Public Health Officer, said =
in a<br>statement, "The County recommends that people ask where oysters wer=
e<br>harvested when eating out or getting food from wholesale locations to<=
br>avoid consuming Rocky Point oysters from Bahia Salina, Sonora, Mexico.<b=
r>It's also important for anyone who is sick to seek medical care.<br>Peopl=
e who are ill, and those that live with them, should wash their<br>hands fr=
equently to avoid contaminating surfaces and foods that could<br>further sp=
read the infection."=0D<br>=0D<br>People who are higher risk for developing=
 serious complications from<br>food poisoning should think about avoiding r=
aw or undercooked oysters<br>and other shellfish. They include the elderly,=
 the very young,<br>pregnant women, people with chronic illnesses like diab=
etes, and those<br>with compromised immune systems. Eating raw oysters has =
been linked to<br>_Vibrio_, _Shigella_, norovirus, and _E. coli_ outbreaks =
in the past.=0D<br>=0D<br>[Byline: Linda Larsen]=0D<br>=0D<br>--=0D<br>Comm=
unicated by:=0D<br>ProMED<br><br>[Norovirus, initially called the Norwalk v=
irus, was one of many<br>viruses named after the location from which the ag=
ent was first<br>isolated, in this case Norwalk, Ohio.=0D<br>=0D<br>Uncooke=
d shellfish are a common vehicle for norovirus infection as<br>well as othe=
r bacterial, viral and toxin diseases.=0D<br>=0D<br>Norovirus can be transm=
itted by:=0D<br>- Eating food or drinking liquids that are contaminated wit=
h<br>norovirus;=0D<br>- Touching surfaces or objects contaminated with noro=
virus and then<br>putting your fingers in your mouth; or=0D<br>- Having dir=
ect contact with someone who is infected with norovirus,<br>such as by cari=
ng for them or sharing food or eating utensils with<br>them.=0D<br>=0D<br>T=
he first sign of norovirus is usually a sudden sick feeling, followed<br>by=
 forceful vomiting and watery diarrhea. Some people may also have a<br>rais=
ed temperature (over 38 deg C/100.4 deg F), headaches, stomach<br>cramps, a=
nd aching limbs. Symptoms usually appear 1-2 days after<br>exposure to infe=
ction, but they can start sooner. Most people make a<br>full recovery withi=
n a few days. Apart from the risk of dehydration,<br>the illness is not gen=
erally dangerous, and there are usually no<br>long-lasting effects from nor=
ovirus infection.=0D<br>=0D<br>The following are myths about oysters (adapt=
ed from<br><a href=3D"https://u19268662.ct.sendgrid.net/ss/c/TLh_csrC34X_iX=
pbYoMamwLgbkE5BuGfqVjUrZAtBV_LZMcZFG9NA7QD_MPKTDdSiMJqrCyIT4kV7duVgF1MZp64z=
7R7WM6GtKXlOKnhwak/42y/VfeYPXfjQ6Sy27oRGQQSXg/h3/3VZ9nQN3zUpYCrior_YXGuKUSx=
9sFF2yoozKmxKZnkA">https://www.fda.gov/food/health-educators/raw-oyster-myt=
hs</a>):=0D<br>=0D<br>Myth: Eating raw oysters is safe if you drown them in=
 hot sauce, which<br>kills everything.=0D<br>Fact: The active ingredients i=
n hot sauce have no more effect on<br>harmful bacteria than plain water. No=
thing but prolonged exposure to<br>heat at a high enough temperature will k=
ill bacteria.=0D<br>=0D<br>Myth: Avoid oysters from polluted waters and you=
'll be fine.=0D<br>Fact: Many pathogens in oysters have nothing to do with =
pollution.<br>Some harmful bacteria thrive naturally in warm coastal areas =
(such as<br>the Gulf of Mexico) where oysters live.=0D<br>=0D<br>Myth: An e=
xperienced oyster lover can tell a good oyster from a bad<br>one.=0D<br>Fac=
t: These pathogens can't be seen, smelled, or even tasted. Don't<br>rely on=
 your senses to decide if an oyster is safe.=0D<br>=0D<br>Myth: Alcohol kil=
ls harmful organisms.=0D<br>Fact: Alcohol may impair your good judgment, bu=
t it doesn't destroy<br>harmful bacteria.=0D<br>=0D<br>Myth: Eating oysters=
 in months with an "R" in their name is safe.=0D<br>Fact: Even though cold-=
weather-harvested oysters are likely somewhat<br>safer, many oysters come f=
rom warmer climates and are imported into<br>the colder climate.=0D<br>=0D<=
br>Myth: Raw oysters are an aphrodisiac and will cure a hangover.=0D<br>Fac=
t: There is no scientific evidence that either of these commonly<br>held be=
liefs is true.=0D<br>- Mod.LL<br><br>ProMED map:<br>California, United Stat=
